Introduction

Following the tremendous challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic, humanity has reached an important turning point in history, compelled to investigate, and comprehend the complexities of pandemics and their far-reaching implications. As we enter an era where the possibility of future pandemics looms large, it is critical that we strengthen our readiness and response processes. To that purpose, we are doing two independent but interconnected statistical analyses that have the potential to dramatically improve our capacity to predict the consequences of such events, similar to the COVID-19 pandemic.

The fundamental goal of our analytical efforts is to reach conclusions that will allow us to delve deeper into the complex effects of pandemics on various aspects of human existence. Our primary focus is on the investigation of crucial characteristics such as age, habits, and comorbidities, which have emerged as critical determinants in the evolution and outcome of pandemics. We hope to untangle the deep link between these parameters and the trajectory of pandemic-related outcomes through careful investigation and synthesis of multiple data sources.

Our first statistical test delves into hypothesis testing. Here, we aim to determine whether individuals aged 60 and older experience a more significant impact and higher mortality rates in comparison to those aged 18 and below due to COVID. In this context, our null hypothesis asserts that there is no difference in the proportion of COVID-related deaths between individuals above 60 and those below 18, with the difference being equal to 0. Conversely, our alternative hypothesis suggests that the mean difference is greater than 0, indicating a higher impact and mortality rate among the elderly.

In our second statistical test, we focus on investigating potential associations between an individual’s number of pre-existing health conditions and various aspects of COVID. This includes examining the likelihood of testing positive for the virus and mortality. Moreover, we aim to explore how comorbidities interact with factors such as age and gender. The objective here is to unveil the relationships and dependencies that exist between these variables.

The findings of these statistical investigations are not only significant in and of themselves, but also have implications for healthcare and policy. They have the potential to serve as the foundation for developing more targeted and effective response tactics. We hope to provide vital information to government officials, healthcare professionals, and policymakers by identifying the persons most vulnerable to the negative impacts of pandemics. In doing so, we hope to give them the skills they need to make informed decisions, allocate resources wisely, and prioritize treatments for individuals who are at a higher risk than others.


Dataset

The dataset, generously provided by the Mexican government, has been made accessible on Kaggle and has been licensed as a CC0 Public Domain License, allowing users unrestricted utilization. Translated by a Kaggle user, this semi-structured dataset boasts 1,048,576 unique rows and 21 features encompassing anonymized patient-related information, including pre-existing conditions. The data exhibit a predominantly boolean format, utilizing 0 to denote male and 1 for female. Similarly, pre-existing conditions are also encoded as boolean values, with 0 signifying an absence and 1 indicating a presence.

There are also presence of scaled data types ranging from 1 to 5, such as the COVID severity classification, contributing to the dataset’s richness. Additionally, values of 97 and 99 under any feature serve as indicators of missing data. This comprehensive dataset thus presents a valuable resource for researchers and data enthusiasts alike, offering insights into the intricate landscape of patient profiles and health conditions in the Mexican context.


Data Cleaning & Wrangling

We went through several steps to clean up and prepare the data for further analysis. Null values, which are frequently represented as numbers, were replaced with “NA,” as this prevents missing data from distorting later analysis. Furthermore, additional features were cleverly designed to help with deeper insights, such as the generation of age brackets based on predetermined boundaries, segmenting the data into ‘0-13,’ ‘14-19,’ ‘20-35,’ ‘36-49,’ and ‘50+’ age groupings. Standardizing data representation is crucial for ensuring consistency in the dataset. For instance, patient types were converted from ‘1’ and ‘2’ to ‘0’ and ‘1’, and sex was converted to ‘male’ and ‘female’. To facilitate more comprehensive analysis, we introduced additional columns. One such column categorizes comorbidities and the number of diseases. Additionally, we create a ‘mortality’ column that classifies individuals as either ‘Dead’ or ‘Alive,’ and a ‘covid_test_result’ column that categorizes test outcomes as ‘Positive’ or ‘Negative.’

Data Analysis


Initial Exploratory Data Analysis


This violin plot illustrates the distribution of ages for two groups: those who are “Alive” and those who are “Dead”. The width of each violin represents the density of data points at a given age. In summary, living individuals in this dataset tend to be younger, mostly between 25-50, while deceased individuals were mostly aged between 50-75 when they passed away.


The violin plot showcases the distribution of the number of diseases among individuals based on their mortality status. Living individuals (in green) primarily have zero diseases, with a small distribution around one disease. In contrast, deceased individuals (in red) display a more spread-out distribution, primarily around one to three diseases, with some having up to around eight diseases.


The scatterplot, based on 10,000 sampled data, depicts the relationship between age and the number of prior diseases, differentiated by mortality status. Alive individuals (in green) predominantly have fewer diseases across all age groups, with a concentration at zero diseases. Deceased individuals (in red) tend to have a wider range of diseases, with a notable increase in disease count as age advances, especially past 50.


We separated the scatterplot into two groups to help analyze it better. The scatterplot visually separates data on age and the number of prior diseases based on mortality status. For alive individuals (in green), there’s a mild positive correlation between age and diseases, but it’s less pronounced. In contrast, deceased individuals (in red) exhibit a clearer upward trend, suggesting a stronger correlation between age and the number of diseases they had.



1st Statistical Test - Hypothesis Testing


\[ \rm H_0: P_{Age \geq 60} - P_{Age \leq 18} = 0 \\ \rm H_A: P_{Age \geq 60} - P_{Age \leq 18} > 0 \]

In order to test the stated null hypothesis we will conduct a 2-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity correction via a prop.test() to check if the proportions of deaths among the different age groups are the same.

We start by focusing on data from people who have actually tested positive for COVID-19 and break it down further to look closely at different age groups: one for seniors aged 60 and over, and another for kids and teens under 18. By doing this step-by-step, we’re making special sets of data just for these particular age groups among those who have caught the virus. This way, we can really zero in on what’s happening with the oldest and youngest folks who are dealing with COVID-19, giving us a clearer picture within the larger group of everyone who’s tested positive.

sub_df_pos = df %>% filter(covid_test_result == 'Positive')
sub_df_60 = sub_df_pos %>% filter(age >= 60)
sub_df_18 = sub_df_pos %>% filter(age <= 18)


Prop-Test

prop.test(c(x.age_60, x.age_18), c(n.age_60, n.age_18), alternative='two.sided', correct=FALSE)
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity correction
## 
## data:  c out of cx.age_60 out of n.age_60x.age_18 out of n.age_18
## X-squared = 6491, df = 1, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3801871 0.3886265
## sample estimates:
##     prop 1     prop 2 
## 0.40220196 0.01779514

Test Results \ P-value: 0.0000 \ 95% confidence interval: [0.3801, 0.3886]

We are able to compute \(P\)-value of \(2.2 \times e^{-16}\), which is the lowest possible \(P\)-value. This value being less than the level of significance of 0.05 implies a rejection of the null hypothesis.

Thanks to our large dataset, the prop.test() also computes a compact and accurate 95% confidence interval of [0.3801, 0.3886].

Therefore, based on the data, we can infer that the proportion of COVID deaths among the 60+ age group is significantly higher than the under 18 age group. Furthermore, we can be 95% confident that the proportion of 60+ COVID deaths is greater than the sub 18 age group by 0.3801-0.3886. This encompasses the observed difference in mortality rates of 0.3844.

Calculating the actual/observed difference in COVID mortality rates of individuals 60 and over and individuals 18

actual.60_18 = (x.age_60 / n.age_60) - (x.age_18 / n.age_18)
actual.60_18
## [1] 0.3844068


To get a better picture of this confidence interval we have also decided to compute a 95% confidence interval via bootstrapping.

The following shows a distribution for 1000 bootstraps difference in mortality rate:

With this bootstrap method we can determine the 95% confidence intervals for difference in proportions of mortality rates, mortality rates of the 60+ age group and sub 18 age group.


Based on a probability plot of differences computed, it appears to follow a normal distribution as the data points in this plot are located approximately along a straight line, it can be concluded that the selected distribution correctly represents the data.


95% confidence interval for Difference between \(P_{Age \geq 60} - P_{Age \leq 18}\)

qdata(~phat.60_18, c(0.025,0.975), data=phat.60_18.df)
##      2.5%     97.5% 
## 0.3802965 0.3886169

Based on this 95% confidence interval via bootstrapping we can be 95% confident that the difference in COVID mortality rates of individuals 60 and over and individuals 18 and under is between 0.3802 and 0.3886. This reaffirms the outcome obtained from the prop.test previously conducted and the observed difference of 0.3844.

2nd Statistisal Test - Chi-squared Test of Independence


\[ \rm H_0: \text{Co-Morbidities and the factors of interest are independent} \\ \rm H_A: \text{Co-Morbidities and the factors of interest are dependent} \]

As COVID has been heavily associated with co-morbidities, we want to determine if there is any correlation between the number of diseases among an individual and COVID attributes such as whether someone will test positive for COVID and mortality. We will also explore the correlation of co-morbidities with age and gender.

It is important to note that when conducting the following Chi-Square tests for the whole dataset, the p-values for every test will fall well below the 0.05 level of significance. This capability stems from our extensive dataset, allowing us to calculate highly precise p-values and confidence intervals, as exemplified in the preceding hypothesis test. Consequently, R will approach a lower limit of 2.2e-15 for the computed p-value. Likewise, enabling simulated p-values yields a consistent value of 0.0004998 across all Chi-Square tests. Given this outcome, we’ve chosen to investigate Chi-square test results using samples comprised of 500 data points.


First let’s take a look at whether a correlation exists between number of diseases among an individual and status (testing positive for COVID)

\[ \rm H_0: \text{Number of Disease an individual has and their Covid Test Result are independent} \\ \rm H_A: \text{Number of Disease an individual has and their Covid Test Result are not independent} \]


Contingency Table

Given the \(P\)-value of 0.001499 being less than the significance level of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. This means that based on the COVID sample data, there is enough evidence to suggest a significant association between the number of diseases an individual has and their likelihood of testing positive for COVID.

This means that based on the COVID sample data, there is not enough evidence to suggest a significant association between the number of diseases an individual has and their likelihood of testing positive for COVID.

In the context of this research, while the \(P\)-value for this particular sample stands at more than 0.05, indicating a lack of statistical significance, the \(P\)-value derived from the entire population data is less than 0.05. Although the sample suggests no significant relationship, the aggregate population data tells a different story, highlighting a statistically significant association.

Conclusion

The findings from both traditional proportion tests and bootstrap methods indicate that individuals aged 60 and above have a significantly higher mortality rate due to COVID-19 compared to individuals aged 18 and under. Both tests reaffirm the observed differences within the dataset thanks to the tight 95% confidence intervals.

Our Chi-Square tests provided insights on comorbidities and other factors of interest. With the entire dataset of around 1.5 million data points at our disposal, we were able to compute a near zero \(P\)-value across all Chi-Square tests. Given the substantial number of data points we input into the chi-squared test, it is anticipated that it may detect some form of association between the factors, even if this association is influenced by external variables.

As anticipated, the results indeed revealed a significant link between the quantity of pre-existing health conditions and several variables, including COVID-19 test outcomes, COVID-19 severity, age, and gender. Furthermore, a noteworthy connection was established between comorbidities and the mortality rate, with mortality rates rising as the number of comorbidities increased.

To generate more realistic insights, we reproduced our studies by analyzing 500 random data points. While the majority of the results were similar to those obtained from assessments of the complete dataset, several variations led to different conclusions. Notably, our investigation indicated that severity and gender appeared to be uncorrelated with comorbidities. This finding, based on our sample approach, lends credence to the claim that it constitutes a more accurate conclusion. As we have seen, the large size of the dataset can make Chi-square tests prone to consistently identify relationships. This assumption is supported by the graphical representation, which clearly indicates independence between gender and comorbidities, as well as between comorbidities and severity. Consequently, our findings support the notion that employing a sampling approach may enhance the accuracy of Chi-square tests, particularly in contexts where the sensitivity of these tests in large datasets can inadvertently indicate relationships.

Our study underscores the profound impact of age and comorbidities on COVID-19 outcomes, emphasizing the need for targeted interventions, especially for older individuals and those with multiple diseases.
